---

EVM Contracts

The EVM implementation consists of five contracts and two public interfaces.


---

ERC5564Announcer

A minimal singleton contract implementing ERC-5564 announcement events.

The contract contains:

no storage

no ownership

no access control


Public function:

announce(...)

Emits:

event Announcement(
    uint256 indexed schemeId,
    address indexed stealthAddress,
    address indexed caller,
    bytes ephemeralPubKey,
    bytes metadata
);


---

ERC6538Registry

Implements the ERC-6538 stealth meta-address registry.

Public functions:

registerKeys(...)
registerKeysOnBehalf(...)
stealthMetaAddressOf(...)

Features:

delegated registration

EIP-712 signatures

replay-protected nonces

DOMAIN_SEPARATOR

per-user nonce management



---

StellarGuruSender

Atomically transfers assets while publishing a stealth announcement.

Uses:

OpenZeppelin ReentrancyGuard


Supports:

sendETH(...)
sendERC20(...)
batchSendETH(...)
batchSendERC20(...)

Capabilities:

ETH transfers

ERC20 transfers

optional ETH gas tip

atomic transfer + announcement

batch operations


The constructor receives the deployed announcer contract address.


---

StellarGuruNames

Privacy-preserving .guru name registry.

Maps human-readable names to stealth meta-addresses.

Public functions:

register(...)
registerOnBehalf(...)
update(...)
release(...)
resolve(...)
nameOf(...)

Validation rules:

3–32 characters

lowercase

alphanumeric only


Ownership is proven using secp256k1 spending-key signatures.

Signature verification:

ecrecover(
keccak256(
"\x19Ethereum Signed Message:\n32" ||
keccak256(name || metaAddress)
))

The contract also supports reverse lookup from stealth meta-address to registered name.


---

StellarGuruWithdrawer

Implements an EIP-7702 delegation target for sponsored withdrawals.

Public functions:

withdrawETH(...)
withdrawERC20(...)
withdrawETHDirect(...)
withdrawERC20Direct(...)

Supports both:

sponsor-paid withdrawals

self-funded withdrawals


Designed to allow stealth addresses to move assets without requiring the stealth address itself to initially hold native gas tokens.
Stellar Contracts

The Stellar implementation is written using Soroban and provides the same stealth address infrastructure as the EVM implementation while following Soroban best practices.

Each contract is intentionally minimal and performs a single responsibility.


---

stealth-announcer

The stealth-announcer contract is a stateless event emitter.

It stores no persistent state and performs no access control.

Public function:

pub fn announce(
    env,
    caller,
    scheme_id,
    stealth_address,
    ephemeral_pub_key,
    metadata
);

Responsibilities:

Emit stealth announcement events

Preserve announcement metadata

Support multiple announcement schemes

Maintain zero on-chain storage



---

stealth-registry

The stealth-registry contract maps Stellar addresses to stealth meta-addresses.

Public functions:

pub fn register_keys(
    env,
    registrant,
    scheme_id,
    stealth_meta_address
);

pub fn stealth_meta_address_of(
    env,
    registrant,
    scheme_id
) -> Bytes;

Requirements:

Caller authorization (require_auth())

Stealth meta-address must be exactly 64 bytes

Existing registrations may be updated

Lookup must return the registered stealth meta-address


Features:

Authorization-gated registration

Constant-time lookup

Multi-scheme support



---

stealth-sender

The stealth-sender contract performs atomic transfers together with stealth announcements.

Public functions:

pub fn init(
    env,
    admin,
    announcer
);

pub fn send(
    env,
    caller,
    token,
    stealth_address,
    amount,
    scheme_id,
    ephemeral_pub_key,
    metadata
);

pub fn batch_send(
    env,
    caller,
    token,
    stealth_addresses,
    amounts,
    scheme_id,
    ephemeral_pub_keys,
    metadatas
);

Features:

Atomic transfer and announcement

Native asset support

Token transfer support

Batch transfers

Announcement forwarding through the deployed announcer contract



---

stellar-guru-names

The stellar-guru-names contract provides the .guru privacy-preserving name service.

Public functions:

pub fn register(
    env,
    caller,
    name,
    meta_address
);

pub fn update(
    env,
    caller,
    name,
    new_meta_address
);

pub fn release(
    env,
    caller,
    name
);

pub fn resolve(
    env,
    name
) -> Bytes;

pub fn name_of(
    env,
    meta_address
) -> String;

Storage:

SHA-256 hashed name keys


Validation:

3–32 characters

Lowercase letters

Alphanumeric only


Features:

Reverse lookup

Ownership verification

Privacy-preserving storage

Efficient name resolution



